properties.Description:
Join us in reading Dr. King's "Where Do We Go From Here: Chaos or Community?"

We will host a discussion about Dr. King's book, including it's role in Andrew Yang's vision for creating universal basic income, on MLK day at Cypress & Grove. All are welcome.

[From Wiki]
Where Do We Go from Here: Chaos or Community? is a 1967 book by African-American minister, Nobel Peace Prize laureate, and social justice campaigner Martin Luther King, Jr. Advocating for human rights and a sense of hope, it was King's fourth and last book before his assassination. He spent a long period in isolation, living in a rented residence in Jamaica with no telephone, composing the book.It later lapsed out of print until Beacon Press published an expanded edition in 2010, which featured a new introduction passage by King's long-time friend Vincent Gordon Harding and a foreword by King's wife, Coretta Scott King. The book received critical acclaim, its revamped version being highlighted as a 2011 University Press Book for Public and Secondary School Libraries and recommended for use in teaching.

Ambassadors of humor featuring Ellis Rodriguez take the stage Thursday, Jan. 2, in a campaign fundraiser for presidential candidate Andrew Yang at Laughs Unlimited in Old Town Sacramento.

The jokesters includes Alyssa Cowan, Dauood Naimyar, Steph Garcia, D-Tyler and host David Lew hope to veto somber attitudes at the 8 p.m. show. Admission is $30 pre-sale and $40 the night of the event. Pre-Sale tickets will come with a limited edition commemorative event button.

Born in Boston, Rodriguez is a U.S. Marine veteran, raised by loving immigrant parents from Panama. Living in a multi-racial, uni-cultural family gave him a unique perspective on life. He grew up speaking Spanish at home, English at church, and Ebonics in school. Having done his comedy on Shaq’s All-Star Jam, Fox’s “Laugh’s On,” and Kevin Hart’s “Hart of the City.”

Garcia, a Roseville resident, known for her quick wit and ferocious sarcasm. Plus she’s married to a U.S. Marine. She’s been on Food Network’s Worst Bakers in America, The View’s Funniest Housewife in America, and Good Day Sacramento’s NAILED IT series.

Naimyar placed third in the 2018 San Francisco International Stand-Up Comedy Competition, and was a finalist in the San Jose Improv Comedy Competition and the Rooster T. Feathers Comedy Competition in Sunnyvale.  Dejan Tyler’s debut album Get Rich or Diabetes is now streaming on Pandora, gives snapshots of real life, for real people, rendered in ridiculous scenarios. Dejan celebrates the lower-middle class with sharp, detailed and flavorful writing.

Sacramento’s Alyssa Cowan likes to podcast, is a member of the Yang Gang, and loves to watch a lot of pro wrestling.

We NEED Illinoisans to sign delegate petitions. Without these delegate signatures, we won't be able to get delegates to the convention to vote, even if Andrew is on the ballot.

Here's the situation: we are in danger of falling short in at least half of our districts.

By my count, half of our districts are still only around 200 signatures; we need at least 500 per district.

I get it; this is a really busy time and it can be hard to sacrifice what little time there is to collect signatures in the cold. It's easy to feel the burnout from work, politics, life. Especially as family, friends, and the holidays are fast approaching. I know these feelings too well.

But that's exactly why we need to do this. Because we're doing this for our family and friends.

This can seem a daunting task, but we've been through harder. That's why I am confident that we can make one final, coordinated push! If there's one thing that Yang Gang is known for, it's that we are both dreamers and doers.

Let's make Andrew proud
